{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3db8ed06-f5be-433d-b90a-f4b4f9ffca84","content":"The most likely issue is that the **.NET Android build system doesn't use `JAVA_HOME`** from your shell by default. It has its own Java discovery logic and may not be finding your Temurin installation.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **Explicitly tell MSBuild where Java is:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$JAVA_HOME\"\n   ```\n\n2. **Or set it permanently in your project** (`.csproj` or `Directory.Build.props`):\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Or install Microsoft's OpenJDK via the workload** (auto-detected by the build):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet workload install android\n   ```\n   This bundles a compatible JDK that the build tools find automatically.\n\n**Verify your `JAVA_HOME` path** ends with `/Contents/Home` — a common macOS gotcha:\n```bash\necho $JAVA_HOME\n# Should be: /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n# NOT:       /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d8a8889-cc92-4d06-85f3-cf7f6a84f726","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nThis is a common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds. The problem is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK has specific Java version requirements. Let me think about what's likely wrong:\n\n1. .NET MAUI (specifically the Android SDK/build tools) requires JDK 11 for older versions, or JDK 17 for newer versions (.NET 8+). JDK 17 should be fine for recent .NET MAUI.\n\n\n2. Even though JAVA_HOME is set and `java -version` works, the .NET Android build tools might not be picking up the Java installation correctly on macOS due to a path resolution issue.\n3. The most likely culprit is that JAVA_HOME needs to point to the exact Adoptium Temurin installation path on macOS, which is typically `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n4. Though there's also the possibility that .NET 9 has different JDK requirements than .NET 8, or that Adoptium Temurin isn't being recognized by the build system. But more importantly, I'm realizing that MSBuild doesn't actually use JAVA_HOME by default on macOS—it has its own detection logic, so I'd need to explicitly set the `JavaSdkDirectory` property in the project file to point to the correct JDK location.\n\n5. The .NET Android workload has its own Java detection mechanism and might be looking specifically for Microsoft's OpenJDK distribution rather than Temurin. With .NET 8+, using the Microsoft OpenJDK or explicitly setting the path is the recommended approach.\n\n6. Without seeing the exact error message, the most likely culprits are either MSBuild can't locate Java at all, or there's a version compatibility issue between the JDK and the Android build tools that MAUI is using.\n\n7. On macOS specifically, the typical gotcha with Adoptium Temurin is that the `JAVA_HOME` path needs to include `/Contents/Home` at the end—something like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` rather than just the `.jdk` directory itself. But since `java -version` works for the user, that suggests the shell environment is fine, so the issue is likely that MSBuild isn't picking up the environment variable properly.\n\nThe real problem is probably that .NET MAUI's Android build on macOS doesn't automatically respect the `JAVA_HOME` variable the way you'd expect—the MSBuild targets have their own Java discovery logic. The solution usually involves explicitly setting `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file or build configuration.\n\nBut with .NET 8 specifically, there's another layer: the Android workload can automatically download and use Microsoft's OpenJDK build, which might be conflicting with or bypassing the Temurin installation entirely. The build could be finding a different JDK or not recognizing the Temurin one at all.\n\nThe most practical solution for macOS is ensuring the .NET Android SDK's Java discovery mechanism either finds the Temurin JDK or gets explicitly pointed to it—either through environment variables passed to MSBuild or by letting the Android workload use its bundled OpenJDK instead. The real issue is likely that the IDE isn't passing the JAVA_HOME environment variable to MSBuild, even though it's set in the shell. I should focus on the most practical fix: explicitly configuring the JavaSdkDirectory in the project file or as a build parameter, since that's what consistently resolves this for .NET MAUI Android builds on macOS. tools bundled with .NET expect the Microsoft OpenJDK.\n\nStarting with .NET 8, the `microsoft-net-sdk-android` workload checks for Java in this specific order:\n1. `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property\n2. The bundled Microsoft OpenJDK (installed via workload)\n3. `JAVA_HOME` environment variable\n4. Registry/system paths\n\nIf the Microsoft OpenJDK workload pack isn't installed and the build can't locate Java through its detection logic, it'll fail even if JAVA_HOME is set.\n\nThe quickest solution is to explicitly set `JavaSdkDirectory` pointing to the JDK, or install the Microsoft OpenJDK workload which bundles everything needed.","outputTokens":2491,"requestId":"E833:12D387:25E5FFF:29F2626:69F93F2C"},"id":"d7b653f2-48b3-474c-9ef3-17b302de7b97","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:52:42.403Z","parentId":"020ad7fb-83c2-4148-b357-d2be4103072f"}
